The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer practically all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
He'll probably be here soon.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunication Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to be reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack competition you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, since we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), said that there is no longer any place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market that brought about a significant drop in prices, to which the classic operators had to react as well.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is room for this type of operators and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look too far for examples.
In February of this year we inform you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
After only half a year, this operator managed to get more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
Moreover, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large expenses in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low expenses - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, are often counterbalanced with the offer of tighter services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap as the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows it can be a good hit also betting on a non-trivial target group.
This operator is specifically addressed to man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator he likes and can trust,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could catch on in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the offer of services it is relatively saturated "
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told mobil.cz by phone.
Indirectly he assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather the opposite, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said the group's spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So, maybe they're flashing better times.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly already at the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has approached us with any complex and serious project in this field," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, a spokesman for Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2, told mobil.cz.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2’s opinion, adds: “To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to be developed.”
“On the T-Mobile network, it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short horizon.
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider it as the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is to find the partner with whom to establish a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a drop in prices and with it, a decline in profits.
So why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull on the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of U:fon’s entry by T-Mobile.
This is attested by the public information accessible on the web pages of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument as to why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: “Furthermore, it wasn’t long ago that the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened up to a fourth operator.
As far as the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services, great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the sheer disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, she expressed her typical position on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
To date, no agreement has been closed because the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for classic operators," Kristián Chalupa, from the Department of Foreign Affairs of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS, added to our question.
These statements are not surprising to the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration; apart from that, they should note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the drop in prices of mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market means and the drop in prices are not in the interest of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Really what is dramatically shocking in this whole case lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position therefore they do not have a corresponding increase of responsibility in their actions in the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," Chalupa added to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of conflict.
There is obviously an analysis of relevant markets prepared by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> according to which telecommunications are, from the point of view of commercial tendering, a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge, an agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator – with all its logic – has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for UOHS it should represent a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly similarly.
The current complaints from the interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they encounter many similar impediments.
Carrying the responsibility on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have met with him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately recently a new amendment to the Telecommunications Law was presented for the expansion of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s competence in the field of commercial tenders which was not carried out, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be perfectly known by the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS, but it is evident that their interests are elsewhere.
All is well when no one is looking
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator still operates unnoticed, and there are already quite a few of them on the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
Usually these are companies that are dedicated to multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few chosen ones get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
“If cases like the ones you cite were discovered, we could talk about breach of contract conditions that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given society,” Martina Kemrová responded to the question on this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that an activity of this kind carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned that thousands of customers may be involved.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make a not inconsiderable profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible so much percent of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that the SIM card of their phone is not in their name so they can not absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the operators. "
Precisely this is what should seem to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> minimally strange.
In addition, a new question appears for the UOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to this type of procedure, why are they blocking the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has enough competence to discover this type of activities and if it is not going to want it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator in the mobile phone market brought a significant decline in the prices of services.
At the same time, in practically every country where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators more or less tried to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market eventually too saturated, problems with service quality, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have intervened and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether it was formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to get the first virtual operator to emerge and with it more began to emerge.
Unfortunately, this whole case is being handled by the Czech Regulatory Authority as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let us not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators lets in a virtual mobile operator it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we will perhaps stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
