Prague’s MHD takes us Wednesday for the first time with the chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company the date on which the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
It can be purchased right now by almost one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it onto their chip card at the transport company’s infocentres and stations in the Metro, Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD> Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>l, Roztyly, Let<0xC5><0x88>rovany, Kobyany stations.
The vouchers can already be purchased yesterday on the internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce, can definitely start to forget about the ticket stands in the metro stations, where until now they had to regularly queue to get a normal ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard is recharged at one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
“In these places there is a window available to passengers with trained staff that helps those interested with the purchase online and also with the reloading of the purchased voucher on their card,” said project spokesman Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>.
