Hidden by the expansion of the theme park of the great Orlando, a few kilometers from the bright, noisy and colossal city, is a quiet village, where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are very evident.
Eatonville, the first fully black incorporated city in the country and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: “the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 colored men, 300 good swimmers, many guavas, two schools, and not a single jail.”
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Fair in Eatonville to pay tribute to Mrs. Hurston, Harlem’s most famous Renaissance writer.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described—making it also a tourist stage by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Depression Season Federal Writers Project—remains a place apart.
The city remains independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Mrs. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their true ideas with the white man, who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even now, in the year that a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has drawn attention to begin a dialogue on the issue of race, many remain wary in front of the outsider.
“We’re very cautious about the way our story is told,” said Jones Hortense, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is at the same time a historical model of black affirmation and a community of nearly 2,400 people living under a poverty level twice the national average.
It is a literary center, but also a repaired example of the rural culture of the Black South—sometimes disdained, sometimes praised—that was born of slavery in America.
No wonder, if those who reside here are both proud and reserved.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really began with Zora, as no one here calls her Mrs. Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through her deep dialect books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a highway that runs through central Florida often forgotten into black history and human drama.
Faced with cement in both life and literature, Mrs. Hurston took her readers to the store owned by Eatonville’s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then into more private areas.
"Off the road on the left," he wrote, "is the modern Maroon public school with its white finishes, its well-maintained gardens and playgrounds, cared for by Howard Miller, as he can hardly read and write."
She also mentions the widow Dash's new husband and writes that Glenn Lee "sells drinks of all kinds and anything goes with transient rooms."
Therefore, in just a few hundred words, Mrs. Hurston relates Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Evidently, this Fodor did not.
In fact, not everyone appreciated the portrait.
“Zora described it as it was,” said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls whom Ms. Hurston immortalized by quoting men who were singing colorless songs about their beauty.
He added: "Some people didn't like that."
Ms. Hurston is still remembered here as a vivacious eccentric who returned frequently after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Franklin Augusto, 77, remembers that when Mrs. Hurston arrived in town, she did so without warning in a large Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today is proud to dress with dignity.
Most residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed sarcastically.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin continues.
But, he adds, swinging in his chair in a backyard overlooking Sabelia Lake, where Ms. Hurston was probably baptized, “she never stayed too long.”
When Mrs. Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were no longer in print.
Like most of the world, Eatonville also seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only woman of color at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had been living.
In Eatonville, there were no major memorial ceremonies, no major public readings.
“I don’t think her contribution to the world or her heritage was understood,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a 2003 biography of Ms. Hurston.
A certain turn came in the '80s.
Orange County officials wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the labor community’s main two-lane street.
The expansion of the Orlando area had already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to his relatively idyllic isolation from the community.
In the 1950s, the struggle for racial mixing brought hatred closer to the community.
