“I wasn’t hugging your teacher because she was white — there’s a cultural gap there,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped create the space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writers, actors, and artists who went above and beyond prejudices, just as she did, with buoyant, confident lines like, “How can anyone deny himself the pleasure of my company!
I don't understand it."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker went to Mrs. Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to resurrect her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Mrs. Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway appeared in bookstores, reintroducing her to the American canons.
The road project came just as Eatonville’s most famous daughter was back in the spotlight.
And this time, Mrs. Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
