Interior wants the driver with three administrative penalties for alcohol, have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents starting the drunk vehicle, or if it is not blown.
The initiative was already announced last June and is now included in the annual report of the Attorney General’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its purpose is the reinsertion of the driver, so he will also receive a road reeducation course.
In addition to the Attorney General for Road Safety, the General Directorate of Traffic (DGT) and the Technological Institute for Automobile Safety (FITSA) Foundation will participate in the experience.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists reported more than once for drunk driving return to take the car.
The alcolock would avoid it since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in expired air and prevents starting the car if the driver does not blow abtes; or when a concentration of alcohol is detected it is higher than that allowed.
Its cost is over 1,000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned.
In this sense, a study carried out in the US in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with these devices reduce infringements by up to 65% during the first year of implementation.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people every year.
The measure confines itself to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address such behaviour before it leads to criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since the legal reform can be done by the ordinary way, and yet the necessary reform by the criminal way requires a reform in an organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial modality, although it has already been implemented experimentally in some industrial and public service vehicles.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote tomorrow on an initiative of the PSOE in which it intends to install this system on school buses, as has been carried out in France.
