Sleep talk
Some children talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up very smart telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while sleeping.
The first time it happens you might get a scare, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somniloquies.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one of you has been told that you spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its occurrence.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting (sleep peeing) or sleepwalking, but it does not have to be that way.
As we have already mentioned, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitement.
However, it is an understudied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or quite the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches ...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any question that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives way in this way.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep alteration that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress situation).
What can be done is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid shows or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and find it hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once sleepiness appears, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything about what has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even if he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember that if you are very anxious during several episodes it would be advisable to consult or find out what generates so much anxiety in the child.
If what he says is understood (which is not the most usual thing), do not fall into the temptation to make an interrogation to extract information from him.
You will get nothing, because when you are asleep you are not conscious enough to organize your thinking.
Also you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing bad, it’s an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
