The interview - Blood is safe again
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective providers of blood in the world.
And above all, it regained the public’s trust that had been seriously shaken by the tainted blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer be reproduced.
While Judge Krever was slow to present their relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Corporation to supply all other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec,” recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained the public’s trust,” he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that “trust is an extremely fragile thing.”
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we install exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nuclide acid tests that make it possible to detect the presence of the virus directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until now were based.
Nucleic acid tests shortened the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
This substantially reduces the risk that certain donors will unknowingly become infected and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly lowered the risk of getting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products every year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to regain health without worries," says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
It is never known which pathogen might emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary said, before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
" Needs increase as the population ages.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which comprises on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All healthy, 18-year-olds who meet the eligibility criteria can still donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we were able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since current life is so rampant, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating her blood,” says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, the placing in the bank of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and it is expected to draw more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts early next year,” says Dr. Décary who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Many moms are disappointed not to be able to enjoy this ", since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
