The Orwellian Discourse of Barrick Gold
In its Sept. 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the largest gold company in the world attempted a €6 million defamation suit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a “transparent public debate”.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation prosecutions, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will gag the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is in front of public opinion that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually made by the change of ideas and not by clubbing.
It was enough for the mining company to open its books, its files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects the petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can call for a "public" debate by disregarding the latter's views?
According to the vice president, it seems that this word refers only to high-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does so mostly because it rejects the mining’s brutal way.
This public is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but on the basis of civilized changes of argument, and not in the framework of what many people perceive as a gag-chase (pursuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a requirement regarding the authors of Noir Canada urging them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the Barrick Gold trial is a direct attack on the freedom of university search and truth, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and make a debate about the facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under pain of many persecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the Noir Canada authors.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The excessive persecution of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what he claims, he does not want to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, but also for public debate in Canada, and it is high time that governments put in place measures to limit this kind of abusive persecution.
Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally agreed yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan that aims to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by the elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money invested, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of control over the salaries paid to the leaders of the companies rescued.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
“We are making great progress toward an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Bush Administration Representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done to shield the economy and ordinary Americans from the current crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
"It's the bottom line: If we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruptions to Americans' daily lives will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last hours because they feared the effect that a new failure in the mood of investors would cause.
The last time they had set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who have joined the negotiations late, were rather favorable to the agreement, without forgetting, however, to express their discontent at being forced to reach this extremity.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly the one that would allow owners to keep their domicile and the one on the salary of the leaders of the surviving companies by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of some, we should not congratulate ourselves.
But these measures are necessary,” he said on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, asked on another network whether he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope to vote on it."
“The important points I read [show] that it is something that we will have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
He said the option of doing nothing is not acceptable.”
The $700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky and unsaleable debts of American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans before spreading to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and causing a liquidity freeze and a disbandment of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement last week.
We believe we have come out of the impasse since Democrats accepted that certain “toxic” assets of distressed companies are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
With the goal of smoothing over the rough edges for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision stipulating that if the government had to assume losses for five years under this program, it could impose new rates that would purport to help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion to which another 100 billion can be added if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote by Congress.
In return for their help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will earn it dividends in case of profits and that it can resell when the storm passes.
The federal government will have the possibility of delaying foreclosure procedures concerning homes obtained with real estate loans under this plan, as well as setting limits on the remuneration and cash compensation paid to the leaders of the companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives from today and to that of the Senate next Wednesday.
Despite all his efforts, he is still not sure that his plan will be approved.
Some people continued to protest yesterday against this bill, both on the part of Republicans and Democrats.
Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, declared to his constituents that “clearly, Washington does not want to understand.”
"We have a very serious financial problem.
There are solutions.
But not the one that’s about taking advantage of taxpayers.”
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, who is a cheerleader for a small group in Congress, presents the problems differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred economics professors, including three Nobel Laureates, wrote to us to tell us: we ask Congress not to hurry and carefully examine the path to be taken,” he declared yesterday.
At this very moment, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an urgent meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was giving up buying its competitor in bankruptcy since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion dollars) during the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is part of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
Instead, we regained a voting right in the bank and influence.
It’s just something savers and families will appreciate now that times are uncertain.”
