Psychology of Overlapping: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological-economic underpinnings of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in an auction and in the meantime the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the “self-prize” mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to the scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against a person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, testing the neurologists’ hypothesis, group members who played “against failure” were willing to bet even more than members of the control group and the “winner” group.
“These results cannot be inferred from any previously existing economic theory.
For those until now explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University’s School of Economics.
Hepatitis: When should I go to the doctor?
Around 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that 100,000 people are infected in this country, but only 7,000 receive treatment because many of the patients do not know they are infected.
The term hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogenic agents and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses in dependence on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (for example with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and with body humors (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
It is advisable for travelers to protect themselves with vaccines against virus A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, it is manifested by poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that jaundice appears on the skin and on the whites of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, dark-colored urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people worldwide die from liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can lead to liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most of the infected do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early recognition, systematic medical control is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who have tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world with chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory check-up as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has a cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the organism, so it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
It aims to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less those who believe in God?
According to the result of recent research, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in which way influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of this unique experiment, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were given electric shocks while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was possible to verify that the Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of investigations in which, together with academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate.
The analysis took place as follows; they fixed a sparkling instrument to the left hand of the patient, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, a 17th-century work by Sassoferrato and Leonardo da Vinci’s Lady with an Ermine from the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo’s oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought that it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while watching either the religious-themed painting or the other.
The Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt "secure" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and peace reigned in their hearts."
Looking at the religious-themed painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can get a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, as for a mother or a father," - said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the outcome of the inquiry.
“The exercise of faith should and in many cases does change our personality,” Wright said.
After these formidable results, only one question remains: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or of another painter of his stature?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On its tenth birthday, Google can say: it can be found both in people’s pockets and in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which doctors they visit and what they are interested in.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who draw a parallel with the Orwellian view do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to gather as much personal data about its users as possible, and this is necessary in order to meet the original goals of Google’s founders: “Let’s bring together all the information in the world in one system!”
According to the leader of Google, the company even after ten years of work that revolved the world is still in the initial phase of the effort to be able to process all the information.
To the question what is going to happen in five years Schmidt answered like this: I would like Google to be able to answer questions like “What to do tomorrow?” or “What would be the job that would be best for me?” - however, software will not be able to answer seemingly so simple questions as long as there is not enough information from users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their browsing on the Internet the searched keywords, IP addresses and the pages where they went at the end of the search are accurately stored.
Thanks for example to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, can re-check what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - in this same logic will be based the Recommendations, in which the system will offer us products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What will happen if they take advantage of my data against myself, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who worry about seeing the information monopoly of Google.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, yearning for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a fact already confirmed that not only retain, but in justifiable cases also cede to third parties all the sought expressions, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most debated example of recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google handed over to the Brazilian government the information from its website, called Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
On the other hand, Internet users who are concerned about the rights of people, in the month of May were relieved when the company together with the EFF, organization for the defense of electronic rights, proved successfully before the court that it was right in its litigation with the FBI: according to the ruling, it will not be able to force Google, through any of the points of the constitution to provide any type of information requested in secret by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government managed to get under the pretext of strengthening the child protection law passed years ago, about fifty thousand Web addresses and about a thousand searched phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of Web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
This is how the opinion about Google is quite contradictory: it is criticized by those who are afraid to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy is harmed when they start using Google services, and they rebel against it as against multinational companies with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not so its rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the World, no matter how much they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the free program package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks see precisely the very problematic relationship between people’s rights and the Internet that was produced precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about leaving intentional footprints behind us and leveraging available communication channels, and while the measures of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: showing ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even join them with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, then these can be included in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, you can also have a blog, in which the latest photo galleries that are stored in the Pi automatically appear.
We can know numerous cases from which it follows that for example the bride, seeing the flow of photographs of the next morning from common friends, finds out with whom she spent the previous night her fraudulent boyfriend or they can dismiss the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on his blog about the direction of the company: one thing is certain, the definition of private life was completely revalued.
A person's life "on line" is what he shows of himself - this is the definition that hides behind the conduct of today's youth.
And the one who wants to hide something, or at least intends to dodge Google’s monopoly, can do so (starting for example with the Scroogle that uses Google’s search system, but leaves no traces).
There are many people who do not want to register on the collective pages to prevent them from being found, but they can replace Google's "on line" applications, from text writing software to image and news reading applications with alternative versions which do not connect with gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
Public opinion is almost openly waiting for the day when Google shows its true face.
The company with its current value of 156 billion dollars is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars), the advertising surfaces of AdWords / AdSense threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, while the services that are introduced increasingly quickly also cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft software, but also for other developers.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example, the top management flatly rejected the employees’ protest after doubling the price of the company’s childcare, they considered the unlimited number of employees’ food too expensive, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 the Chinese regime violated good interests and the company under the agreement leaked all the moral information.
One of the internal regulations of the company says that they will not announce any new service in advance, but only when it was already ready to operate, which if it is certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will be able to revolve around the World: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving of books and magazines of Google we can create such full dimensions that the company will soon be cited by the Supreme Court of the United States, others fear of their own health problems.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, will be able to provide a good raw material for science fiction writers, the Scroogled, novel by the popular Cory Doctorow, describes in Orwellian form that future, in which a man only of the Google data can be described alarmingly well.
