The written version of the law of the $700 billion financial rescue package has been prepared, which will be applied in several phases in order to buy the bad loans of the banks.
In the first phase, half of the money will be spent.
According to the schedule of the East Coast during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, the leaders of the congress reached an agreement around the financial rescue package of 700 billion dollars in total, after several days of discussion - reported Reuters.
“We have made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic president of the U.S. Congress, adding that the agreement only needs to be formalized in a document.
The commitment made on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the finance minister, speaking on the outcome of the compromise said: this program will work and will be efficient but other measures are needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the cart of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets, that is, on Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (that is, before 2 a.m. on Monday, according to Central European time), without causing a spectacular jump in the stock markets.
On the bill called the 2008 emergency law for economic stabilization, the U.S. Congress will vote first on Monday, and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the deal.
“We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy,” White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend all $700 billion to buy bad credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this sum the Ministry of Finance will buy securities credit fund, bad rating and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the decision of the president.
This program will be controlled by a special agency, in which the president of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion could be spent after a new congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it will be able to simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and securities of credit fund, in addition to other "poisonous" loans as well.
The purchase can be made in auctions or directly - informed competent people of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the financial portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said: the law ensures the necessary financial means, which can even reach 700 billion dollars to meet the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We do everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it - he added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks that are in trouble and waiting for state aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their indemnities, which the American slang simply calls golden parachutes.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and the limitations depend on the form of aid provided by the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys at auction, an extra tax will be imposed on gold parachutes, unless the failed bank chief retires.
By buying the bad credits directly, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that compensation from the bosses is not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations refer only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the program.
This is the first case in U.S. history that a legal limit on CEOs’ incomes will be in place, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the congressional committee responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since ultimately they can even profit from the transaction as soon as the economy recovers and with it the bank.
Under the bill, the president will have to present a proposal to Congress over the next five years on how to return financial sector losses to taxpayers.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed reservations about the project.
This is not what the American people have entrusted to us, that is, they are not protecting taxpayers’ dollars,” said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
Her fellow Ohio Democrat, Mary Kaptur, said the measures were urged by those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008 domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose 1.1 percent from July 2008 and fell 3.9 percent from a year earlier.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent from the previous month and by 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial selling prices rose only marginally, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic selling prices of the processing industry sectors increased minimally, by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), due primarily to the 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
They did not change the prices of papermaking, publishing houses and printing presses.
In the rest of the sectors of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight within domestic trade, there was an increase of 0.3 percent in August, first of all due to the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector an increase of 13.2 percent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
There was a decline in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally, prices increased by 10.2 percent.
Prices for electricity, gas, heat and water supply were 18.7 percent higher than the previous year’s prices.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly increase in prices (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, while prices in the energy sector and intermediary sectors remained unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediary industry (16.8 percent).
In the branches producing consumer goods, there was a decrease of 6.8 percent and in investment goods 1.4 percent.
The industry’s export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent over the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month decreased by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
