Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic cinemas
The historical cinemas close favouring the Multiplex.
“A city without movie theaters in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the big Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticones in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear almost always are historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared", observes the director of the new Paradiso cinema, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand jury prize at Cannes, which told the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that lost so much.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of merchants, speak for themselves: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and most of them are paid for by the cinemas of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the advent of the multiplex is responsible for its disappearance, these three Italian regions have registered the largest number of new meticone cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, “it would be useful if new structures were built but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its patrons are willing to transfer to the meticons.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of merchants: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that worried about closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect mono cinema both in the historic center and in the periphery.
Among the rules provided for there are tax facilitation measures in favor of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic area and will have special rates for parking.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” observes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna’s example by putting other measures in place.
True, to contrast the extra power of the meticones, the traditional rooms have to improve the quality of the sound and the image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a subject that was always important to me: the closure of the Bagheria cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Paradiso cinema", which I had already thought about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
