When the energy is born from the waves, the big ones come down to the stage
It is an extinct field that occupies more than 70% of the surface of the planet and is now being discovered by the world’s largest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the great like Chevron look.
The possibility of collecting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 70s together with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now that environmental cases and the new increase in oil are giving impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated for 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity need could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of the waves of the sea.
This amount would be double that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 has sealed an agreement to build an implant in the North of Portugal.
When the intention was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away to bet on marine energy are always more and among these companies those who have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology," a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It’s a pretty important sign, considering that in Alaska the U.S. continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to carry out new drilling.
In addition to Chevron is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to follow the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed indicate an increasing interest.
technology to develop.
Experts speak of a technology still at the beginning, because marine energy there is no doubt that it has a great environmental impact.
For now the impacts like those of the Portuguese or the Scots are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, a technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas joined together.
The force of the waves, which makes the boas move up and down becomes hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure spins a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast via submarine cables.
For now there are four implants of this type in development, waiting only for federal approval, apart from energy, could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping center and a parking lot, using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of the water when there are tides, makes the blades of the turbines rotate, creating a rotary movement that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Of particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Development of Electric Power, right now deserves the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is mostly about tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others approaching the coasts, have invested 7.5 million dollars in 2008 and an investment of 35 million is planned for 2009.
